<br>
Just saw the movie and I was pleasantly surprised.  I came into the movie expecting to cringe and wince at every horrible miscue.<br>
<br>
Instead, I loved the grandness of it.  The director is clearly trying to capture the glory of the books.  Anyone who hasn't read them really should give them a real shot.<br>
<br>
They start slow, but builds up so huge that when the 3rd book is over you want to read it all again.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Minor complaints:<br>
<br>
* Elrond looked the part, but I thought he did not capture the tone or wisdom of Elrond at all.  <br>
<br>
* Merry and Pippin were not bumbling idiots as portrayed in the movie.  I guess they got stuck with the dumb-side-kick-for-humor role, but I hope the 2nd movie doesn't make them look so stupid, or weak.<br>
<br>
* I wish Glorfindel had been in the movie, although I understand why they needed to streamline the number of characters.  I just always loved that sequence in the book.  <br>
<br>
* I wish Boromir had a little more fight action before his last scene.  He was the mightiest human warrior, that's why he was there.  <br>
<br>
* Gimli was sad.  John Rhys-Davies is a horrible OVER-actor, and he did it here.  If that was him, I thought so.  That was a shallow portrayal, imho.  <br>
<br>
Best scene:<br>
<br>
* That scene with Galadriel by her mirror freaking rocked.  I loved that.  Worth the price of admission along.<br>
<br>
Most surprising:<br>
<br>
*  Legollas rocked.  I mean he quietly stole a number of scenes.  Graceful, elegant, fluid movement.  <br>
<br>
*  Gandalf rocked.  Christ, he was perfect.<br>
<br>
*  Galadriel rocked.  That part was tremendous.  High Elves ain't little sissies, and she showed why.<br>
<br>
*  How much the movie tried to be faithful to the vision of the books.  <br>
